SIMPLE: pitiful
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Pitiful
<hw>Pit"i*ful</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Full of
pity; tender-hearted; compassionate; kind; merciful;
sympathetic.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The Lord is very <qex>pitiful</qex>, and of tender mercy.</q>
<rj><qau>James v. 11.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Piteous; lamentable; eliciting compassion.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>A thing, indeed, very <qex>pitiful</qex> and horrible.</q>
<rj><qau>Spenser.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To be pitied for littleness or meanness; miserable;
paltry; contemptible; despicable.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>That's villainous, and shows a most <qex>pitiful</qex> ambition in
the fool that uses it.</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- Despicable; mean; paltry. See
<er>Contemptible</er>.</syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p>-- <wordforms><wf>Pit"i*ful*ly</wf>, <pos>adv.</pos> --
<wf>Pit"i*ful*ness</wf>, <pos>n.</pos></wordforms>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Pitiless</ent>⟦br⟧
